<H2><U>
<a name="figures">Important Tsimshian Mythological Figures</a>
</u></H2>

<B><img src="vinesmall.jpg"><font size=4><I><U>Raven</font></U></B></I> (Txaamsm or Wigyet): 
Raven is the culture hero of Tsimshian mythology.
He is a revered and benevolent transformer figure who helps the people and shapes their world for them,
but at the same time, he is also a trickster character, and many Tsimshian stories about Raven have to do with
his frivolous or poorly thought out behavior getting him into trouble. 
Txaamsm is the hero's personal name and is pronounced similsr to chahm-sum (sometimes
also spelled Txa'msem, Txamsem, Txamsen, Chemsem, or other ways) 
Wigyet is pronounced similar to weeg-yet (sometimes also spelled Wiigyet, Wegyet, or We-gyet) and
is an eponym meaning "big man" or "giant." Occasionally he may also be referred to by the name
Gaax (pronounced similar to gawkh), which is the literal Tsimshian word for "raven."
<BR><BR>
<B><img src="vinesmall.jpg"><font size=4><I><U>Property Woman</font></U></B></I>: 
A spirit woman with curly hair who brings prosperity to anybody who catches sight of her.
<BR><BR>
<B><img src="vinesmall.jpg"><font size=4><I><U>Ba'wis</font></U></B></I> (also spelled Bawus, Ba'os, Ba'oosh, Ba'wes, and other ways): 
A hairy sasquatch-like creature of the wilderness. It is reclusive and rarely bothers people.

<H2><U>
<a name="tribes">Tsimshian Indian Folklore</a>
</u></H2>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
http://www.sacred-texts.com/nam/nw/nass/index.htm
">Tsimshian Texts</A></b> <IMG SRC="star.gif" ALT="*"> <b><A HREF="
http://www.sacred-texts.com/nam/nw/tst/index.htm
">New Tsimshian Textst</A>:</b> <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Online books of Tsimshian mythology collected by Franz Boas in the early 1900's.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
https://www.historymuseum.ca/cmc/exhibitions/aborig/fp/fpz2f28e.shtml
">The Winter Hunters and the Mosquito</A>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Tsimshian myth about the origin of mosquitos.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
http://www.native-languages.org/tsimshianstory.htm
">The Theft of Light</A></b> <IMG SRC="star.gif" ALT="*"> <b><A HREF="
http://solar-center.stanford.edu/folklore/raven-and-sun.html
">Raven and the Sun</A></b> <IMG SRC="star.gif" ALT="*"> <b><A HREF="
https://web.archive.org/web/20121116093642/http://www.pyramidmesa.com/tsim2.htm
">The Theft of Light</A>:</b> <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Tsimshian myths about Raven stealing the sun.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
http://solar-center.stanford.edu/folklore/walks-over-sky.html
">One Who Walks All Over The Sky</A>:</b> <IMG SRC="star.gif" ALT="*"> <B><A HREF="
https://web.archive.org/web/20121116093642/http://www.pyramidmesa.com/tsim3.htm
">Walks-All-Over-The-Sky</a>:</b> <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Tsimshian myth about the origin of the sun, the moon, and the night sky.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
http://www.pitt.edu/~dash/animalindian.html#tsimshianbear
">The Bear Who Married A Woman</A>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Tsimshian legend about a woman who became a bear wife.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
http://www.firstpeople.us/FP-Html-Legends/RavenBecomesVoracious-Tsimshian.html
">Raven Becomes Voracious</A>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Tsimshian myth about how Raven acquired his great appetite.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
https://web.archive.org/web/20121116093642/http://www.pyramidmesa.com/tsim1.htm
">The Meeting of the Wild Animals</A>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Tsimshian legend about the origin of the seasons.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
http://www.firstpeople.us/FP-Html-Legends/Wolf_Clan_And_The_Salmon-Tsimshian.html
">Wolf Clan and the Salmon</A>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Tsimshian legend about a volcanic eruption caused by disrespect for the salmon.
<BR>

<H2><U>
<a name="books">Recommended Books on Tsimshian Mythology</a>
</u><BR><font size=2>Our organization earns a commission from any book bought through these links</font>
</u></H2>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"><b><A HREF="
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0889223335/natilangofthe-20
">The Porcupine Hunter and Other Stories</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Collection of Tsimshian legends and folktales.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"><b><A HREF="
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1430458321/natilangofthe-20
">Myths and Legends of Alaska</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Anthology of folklore from the Tsimshian and other Alaskan tribes.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"><b><A HREF="
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0140277714/natilangofthe-20
">American Indian Trickster Tales</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Compilation of more than a hundred stories about Raven and other Native American tricksters.<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
(Use discretion sharing these with kids as some of the stories contain adult humor.)
